Package org.neo4j.kernel.impl.transaction.log.reverse

Class ReversedSingleFileTransactionCursor

  • java.lang.Object
    • org.neo4j.kernel.impl.transaction.log.reverse.ReversedSingleFileTransactionCursor
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    AutoCloseable, Supplier<CommittedTransactionRepresentation>, IOCursor<CommittedTransactionRepresentation>, RawCursor<CommittedTransactionRepresentation,​IOException>, TransactionCursor
    public class ReversedSingleFileTransactionCursor
extends Object
implements TransactionCursor
    Returns transactions in reverse order in a log file. It tries to keep peak memory consumption to a minimum by first sketching out the offsets of all transactions in the log. Then it starts from the end and moves backwards, taking advantage of read-ahead feature of the ReadAheadLogChannel by moving in chunks backwards in roughly the size of the read-ahead window. Coming across large transactions means moving further back to at least read one transaction per chunk "move". This is all internal, so from the outside it simply reverses a transaction log. The memory overhead compared to reading a log in the natural order is almost negligible. This cursor currently only works for a single log file, such that the given ReadAheadLogChannel should not be instantiated with a LogVersionBridge moving it over to other versions when exhausted. For reversing a whole log stream consisting of multiple log files have a look at ReversedMultiFileTransactionCursor. 
    
              ◄────────────────┤                          chunkTransactions for the current chunk, reading readNextChunk().
 [2  |3|4    |5  |6          |7 |8   |9      |10  ]
 ▲   ▲ ▲     ▲   ▲           ▲  ▲    ▲       ▲
 │   │ │     │   │           │  │    │       │
 └───┴─┴─────┼───┴───────────┴──┴────┴───────┴─────────── offsets
             │
             └─────────────────────────────────────────── chunkStartOffsetIndex moves forward in readNextChunk()
    See Also:
    ReversedMultiFileTransactionCursor
